r Noncitizen and Citizen Students: A Conceptual Framework -- t12. Refugees in Education: What Can Science Education Contribute? -- t13. Lost in Transit: Education for Refugee Children in Sweden, Germany, and Turkey -- t14. From the Crisis of Connection to the Pursuit of Our Common Humanity: The Role of Schools in Responding to the Needs of Immigrant and Refugee Children -- t15. Children of Immigrants in the United States: Barriers and Paths to Integration and Well-Being -- t16. Improving the Education and Social Integration of Immigrant Students -- tEpilogue: Pope Francis on Migration -- tLIST OF CONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe world is witnessing a rapid rise in the number of victims of human trafficking and of migrants-voluntary and involuntary, internal and international, authorized and unauthorized. In the first two decades of this century alone, more than 65 million people have been forced to escape home into the unknown. The slow-motion disintegration of failing states with feeble institutions, war and terror, demographic imbalances, unchecked climate change, and cataclysmic environmental disruptions have contributed to the catastrophic migrations that are placing millions of human beings at grave risk. Humanitarianism and Mass Migration fills a scholarly gap by examining the uncharted contours of mass migration. Exceptionally curated, it contains contributions from Jacqueline Bhabha, Richard Mollica, Irina Bokova, Pedro Noguera, Hirokazu Yoshikawa, James A. Banks, Mary Waters, and many others. The volume's interdisciplinary and comparative approach showcases new research that reveals how current structures of health, mental health, and education are anachronistic and out of touch with the new cartographies of mass migrations. Envisioning a hopeful and realistic future, this book provides clear and concrete recommendations for what must be done to mine the inherent agency, cultural resources, resilience, and capacity for self-healing that will help forcefully displaced populations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aEmigration and immigrationxHistoryy21st century. 0aHumanitarianism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh  aanachronistic.  acataclysmic environmental disruptions.  aclimate change.  acomparative approach.  acultural resources.  ademographic imbalances.  adisplaced populations.  aeducation.  aescaping home.  afailing states.  afeeble institutions.  agrave danger.  ahuman trafficking.  ainternal.  ainternational.  ainvoluntary.  amass migration.  amental health.  amigrants.  amigrations.  aout of touch.  aself healing.  avictims.  avoluntary.  awar and terror.1 aAbdi, Abdirahman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAbdi, Saida, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAber, J. Lawrence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBanks, James A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerent, Jenna M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBetancourt, Theresa S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBhabha, Jacqueline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBiner, Özge, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBokova, Irina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBorgonovi, Francesca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrul, Maurice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDryden-Peterson, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForman, F